AN IMPERATIVE PURCHASE FOR ANYONE NEW TO THE RPG GENRE. For a PlayStation 1 classic that isn't graphically the best by contemporary standards, it has an engrossing plot, a great cast of characters, and RPG systems which makes it very addictive, especially the Materia system which lets you customize character abilities better than most RPGs. Lots of replay value, too. It's also held sacred by critics & fans alike, so, please, try the game once before dismissing it as an ancient relic!

Overall thos is well worth playing.

If you get the BSOD, install the game, but do NOT play it immediately. Install, then go to Settings, then to Apps, then scroll down to Final Fantasy VII and go to Permissions. In Permissions, allow the game to have access to all permissions available. It's an older app, so while you may not see a need for all of the permissions, it does need them to run! Exit Settings and re-start your device. Run the game and it should work fine! This also works for FF9!!!

"Failed to connect to cloud" with an annoying sound when using my Google account. So the cloud servers seems to have been down since 2015... This makes it very difficult to play between tablets and phone because it means having to manually extract the saves and uploading it myself on a cloud storage. ----------------- Also, my tablet is running android 10, so easy access to DeviceStorage\Android\data\com.square_enix... but my Google Pixel 5 is running Android 11 with the new scoped storage access, meaning I haved had to use a third app to be able to use the old Files app that can still see /Android/Data/... ----------------- It would be much easier if FF7 could let us relocate the directory for the saves. It would then be easy to transfer or use auto sync apps (because if try to auto sync the directory of the game, it will have to store in the cloud the heavy game files as well).

Device: ASUS Zenpad 3s 10 tablet and OnePlus 5 phone. Runs well on tablet 
but will not load on phone. On tablet, it crashes in open world every 30 
minutes but otherwise stable. Dev states it does not run on Android 8.0 
yet, so hopefully will fix soon. It is a true port from the original. No 
graphic updates that I can tell. The tablet controls are as good as could 
be expected from a console port, but that brings me to my primary 
complaint: Please enable controller support! The game was designed for a 
controller originally, so not enabling support for a controller does not 
make any logical sense. I tried using a PS4 and X Box One S controller, and 
neither works seamlessly with the game. The buttons are not re-mappable 
(not without a third party app and root) and the d-pad is sluggish, 
rendering controllers useless right now. Update: Works on all devices 
without issue and works with controller now!

The game itself is an iconic rpg and replaying it has been nostalgic. The graphics shouldn't be rated down since the game was released in 1997. As for controls, the virtual analog is a great thing, but the d-pad in battle is a bit rough - if playing hastily, you may accidentally use the change or defend commands. I don't know how I feel about the added 'max stats' option or the ability to turn random encounters on and off. What is really worth noting is that this app is in serious need of some bug fixes as it crashes every 10 to 20 minutes or so (hence the low rating scores). This wasn't too much of an issue since I just saved constantly - some parts of the game were a little annoying to get through because of this issue. Even so, it won't stop 100% completion of the game.  This would be very close to a five star app if the crashing issue were to be resolved.

As you can imagine being a JRPG that expects players to save frequently, this is a big problem.
